definitions.definition: A structure built or serving as an abode of human beings. [from 9th c.]
examples: This is my house and my family's ancestral home.

subdefinitions.definition: ( Hong Kong , only used in names ) An apartment building within a public housing estate .

definitions.definition: A container; a thing which houses another.
( uncountable ) Size and quality of residential accommodations; housing .
A building intended to contain a single household, as opposed to an apartment or condominium or building containing these.
The people who live in a house; a household . [from 9th c.]
A building used for something other than a residence ( typically with qualifying word ) . [from 10th c.]
examples: The former carriage house had been made over into a guest house .
On arriving at the zoo, we immediately headed for the monkey house .

subdefinitions.definition: A place of business ; a company or organisation, especially a printing press , a publishing company, or a couturier . [from 10th c.]
examples: A small publishing house would have a contract with an independent fulfillment house .

subdefinitions.definition: A place of public accommodation or entertainment, especially a public house , an inn , a restaurant , a theatre , or a casino ; or the management thereof. [from 10th c.]
examples: One more, sir, then I'll have to stop serving you – rules of the house , I'm afraid.

definitions.definition: The audience for a live theatrical or similar performance. [from 10th c.]
examples: After her swan-song, there wasn't a dry eye in the house .

definitions.definition: ( politics ) A building where a deliberative assembly meets; whence the assembly itself, particularly a component of a legislature . [from 10th c.]
examples: The petition was so ridiculous that the house rejected it after minimal debate.

definitions.definition: A dynasty; a family with its ancestors and descendants , especially a royal or noble one. [from 10th c.]
examples: A curse lay upon the House of Atreus.

definitions.definition: ( figurative ) A place of rest or repose . [from 9th c.]
A grouping of schoolchildren for the purposes of competition in sports and other activities. [from 19th c.]
examples: I was a member of Spenser house when I was at school.

definitions.definition: An animal 's shelter or den , or the shell of an animal such as a snail , used for protection. [from 10th c.]
( astrology ) One of the twelve divisions of an astrological chart. [from 14th c.]
( cartomancy ) The fourth Lenormand card.
( chess , now rare ) A square on a chessboard , regarded as the proper place of a piece . [from 16th c.]
( curling ) The four concentric circles where points are scored on the ice . [from 19th c.]
Lotto ; bingo . [from 20th c.]
( uncountable ) A children 's game in which the players pretend to be members of a household .
examples: As the babysitter, Emma always acted as the mother whenever the kids demanded to play house .

definitions.definition: ( US , dialect ) A small stand of trees in a swamp .
( sudoku ) A set of cells in a sudoku puzzle which must contain each digit exactly once, such as a row, column, or 3×3 box.
( American football , slang , with “the” ) The end zone .
